    <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
        <body>
            <div rend="parallel">
                <p xml:id="KT396-kilavi">makaṭ pōkkiya tāy uraittatu. </p>


                <p xml:lang="en">Told by the mother, who had let go the daughter. </p>
            </div>

            <div rend="parallel">
                <lg xml:id="KT396">
                    <l> pālu muṇṇāḷ pantuṭaṉ mēvāḷ</l>
                    <l> viḷaiyā ṭāyamō ṭayarvō ḷiṉiyē</l>
                    <l> yeḷiteṉa vuṇarntaṉaḷ kollō muḷiciṉai</l>
                    <l> yōmai kuttiya vuyarkōṭ ṭoruttal</l>
                    <l> vēṉiṟ kuṉṟattu vevvaraik kavāaṉ</l>
                    <l> maḻaimuḻaṅku kaṭuṅkura lōrkkuṅ</l>
                    <l> kaḻaitiraṅ kāriṭai yavaṉoṭu celavē.</l>


                </lg>

                <lg xml:lang="en">
                    <l> She who wouldn't even drink milk,</l>
                    <l rend="indent7"> who wouldn't wish more than <note place="foot">How to
                        understand <term xml:lang="ta">pantu uṭaṉ mēvāḷ</term> ? It might either be
                        wishing nothing in addition to a ball (as above), or, thus T.V.G., "she
                        wouldn't wish even for the ball [by herself]".</note> a ball,</l>
                    <l> who would be engaged in play with [her] companions – now!</l>
                    <l> Did she feel it would be easy,</l>
                    <l> going with him to a difficult place, where the bamboo dries up,</l>
                    <l rend="indent"> where the bull with high tusks, <note place="foot">From the
                        motif of the pierced tree it is possible to conclude that the animal is an
                        elephant, and accordingly <term xml:lang="ta">kōṭu</term> refers to its
                        tusks.</note> </l>
                    <l rend="indent7"> who pierced the dry-leaved Ōmai tree,</l>
                    <l rend="indent"> listens to the thundering, heavy voice of rain</l>
                    <l rend="indent2"> on the slope of the hot mountain in the hills <note place="foot">What is expressed by the accumulation of <term xml:lang="ta">kuṉṟam, varai</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">kavāaṉ</term>
                        , three words for something like "mountain"?</note> in summer?</l>


                </lg>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
